Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry
produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{9%ounce} on a diagonal into ½-inch-thick pieces.
Halve, peel, and mince @shallot{1}. Roughly chop @walnuts{½%ounce}.

Toss carrots on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{5%teaspoon},
half the @smoky cinnamon paprika spice{1%tablespoon} (you'll use more later),
@salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add
@Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce}, @golden raisins{1%ounce}, and half the shallot;
cook, stirring, until couscous is lightly toasted and raisins and shallot are
softened, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Add half the @chicken stock concentrate{2}, @water{3/4%cup} (1 1/2 cups for 4
servings); bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer and cover. Cook until
couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Pat @pork chops{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with
@garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork and cook
until browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per side.

> If pork is on the thicker side, reduce heat to medium; cover and cook for 2-3
> minutes more per side.

Transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest. Reserve pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add remaining shallot,
a pinch of @salt{}, and pepper; cook, stirring occasionally, until fragrant and
softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @water{1/2%cup} (1 cup for 4 servings), @cranberry jam{1}, remaining stock
concentrate, @smoky cinnamon paprika spice{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4), a pinch of
salt, and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce begins to thicken,
~{3-5%minutes}.

> Be sure to measure the Cinnamon Paprika Spice—we sent more.

Remove from heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4) until melted.
Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Stir walnuts into #pot{} with couscous and season with salt and pepper to taste.
Slice pork crosswise.

Divide pork, couscous, and carrots between plates. Spoon sauce over pork and
serve.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.